      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>The Syracuse based Smith Premier Typewriter Company was founded in 1886 by the gun
            manufacturers Lyman Smith and Wilbert Smith in cooperation with their younger brothers
            Monroe and Hurlburt. The Smith-Premier No.1, an invention of Alexander Timothy Brown,
            was patented in 1889. The new Building for the typewriter production was erected on the
            corner of Syracuse's Clinton and Onondaga Street. The Smith Brothers soon joined a
            consortium of typewriter producers (Remington, Yost, Densmore and Caligraphas) which
            became the Union Typewriter Company. When forced to continue the production of
            blind-writing typewriters despite the growing customer interest in frontstrike visible
            typewriters, the brothers decided to leave the Union Company and founded a new company,
            the L.C. Smith &amp; Bros Typewriter Company (1903). The new Company soon released its
            L.C. Smith &amp; Bros. Models No. 1 and 2 which were both invented by Carl Gabrielson.
            L.C. Smith &amp; Bros. later merged with the Corona Typewriter Company in 1926 to become
            the L.C. Smith &amp; Corona Typewriters Inc.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">L.C. Smith &amp; Bros. Typewriter Co. Collection</emph> consists
            mainly of business correspondence, the major part of which belongs to the era of the
            Smith Premier Typewriter Company (1890-1903). The correspondence related to the L.C.
            Smith &amp; Bros Typewriter Company belongs exclusively to the early phase of that
            company (1904). The few items of printed material are related to the latter company.</p>
      </scopecontent>
